{"id":"1112.3025","submitter":"Matjaz Perc","authors":"Attila Szolnoki, Matjaz Perc","title":"Group-size effects on the evolution of cooperation in the spatial public\n  goods game","comments":"4 two-column pages, 5 figures; accepted for publication in Physical\n  Review E","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. E 84 (2011) 047102","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.84.047102","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.soc-ph cond-mat.stat-mech q-bio.PE","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We study the evolution of cooperation in public goods games on the square\nlattice, focusing on the effects that are brought about by different sizes of\ngroups where individuals collect their payoffs and search for potential\nstrategy donors. We find that increasing the group size does not necessarily\nlead to mean-field behavior, as is traditionally observed for games governed by\npairwise interactions, but rather that public cooperation may be additionally\npromoted by means of enhanced spatial reciprocity that sets in for very large\ngroups. Our results highlight that the promotion of cooperation due to spatial\ninteractions is not rooted solely in having restricted connections amongst\nplayers, but also in individuals having the opportunity to collect payoffs\nseparately from their direct opponents. Moreover, in large groups the presence\nof a small number of defectors is bearable, which makes the mixed phase region\nexpand with increasing group size. Having a chance of exploiting distant\nplayers, however, offers defectors a new way to break the phalanx of\ncooperators, and even to resurrect from small numbers to eventually completely\ninvade the population.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 13 Dec 2011 20:49:34 GMT"}],"update_date":"2011-12-14"}
